Wing size was computed as centroid size (the square root of the sum of squared distance between each landmark and the wing centroid), an isometric estimator of size, and then tested for differences among species, populations and sexes by ANOVA. Shape variables were extracted from the landmark data. Briefly, the raw coordinates were first superimposed (aligned, translated, rotated, and scaled to a unit centroid size) using a generalized orthogonal least-squares Procrustes (GPA) procedure ( Rohlf & Slice 1990 ). Then, the partial warps representing the non-uniform shape variables and uniform components were calculated. The resulting matrix ( w ; ‘weight matrix’ of
Rohlf et al. 1996
) was used for Canonical variate analysis (CVA) to examine pattern of among-species/populations variation in total shape space and to obtain the classification matrix. Visualization of shape changes associated with canonical axes was achieved through deformations obtained by regression w matrix onto canonical axis scores (
Rohlf et al. 1996
). The phenetic relationships among spe- cies/populations were determined by UPGMA cluster analysis ( Sneath & Sokal 1973 ) on squared Mahalanobis distances.
